“For technical fields (math, cs, sciences), it would probably be around a split of 60% direct instruction and 40% discovery. For these fields, direct instruction is what is needed to build the understanding needed to even know how to discover more.”
In my experience it doesn't depend on the subject but on how abstract and theoretical the subject is. If a subject involves lots of doing in my opinion it's certainly more efficient to learn with discovery, on the other hand if a subject is super theory heavy (usually abstract mathematics abstract math-heavy cs/science) it can be more efficient to directly learn from someone else the abstract building blocks don't have to be reinvented. I think traditionally when people say CS, math, or the sciences they are usually referring to fields that have a lot of theoretical complexity, but it's certainly not all or even most technical fields in my opinion.